This is an Android platform change, not just MAUI. `adjustResize` was deprecated in Android API 30+ and is fully removed in edge-to-edge mode (default on Android 15 / .NET 10). The replacement is **WindowInsets**.

### Recommended approach

**1. Use MAUI's built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`** (simplest)

Wrap your chat layout in a `ScrollView` — MAUI automatically adjusts for the keyboard. If you previously disabled it, re-enable it:

```csharp
// In your MainActivity or MauiProgram.cs platform code:
Microsoft.Maui.Platform.KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Connect();
```

**2. If you need manual control** (e.g., a fixed input bar outside a ScrollView), listen to insets in your `MainActivity`:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Compatibility.Platform.Android;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
}

class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var navBar   = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

        // imeInsets.Bottom = keyboard height in px (0 when closed)
        int bottomPadding = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navBar.Bottom);
        v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottomPadding);

        return insets;
    }
}
```

**3. In your XAML**, keep the input bar at the bottom of a `Grid`:

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" ... />
    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

### Key takeaway

Drop the `UseWindowSoftInputModeAdjust` call entirely — it's a no-op now. Option 1 works for most layouts; use Option 2 when you need pixel-level control over how the keyboard pushes your input bar up.
